data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":216,"item_id":"msg_01f6ce18c6bc996900692793067ee0819080a280841826e9ec","output_index":5,"content_index":0,"text":"Wikipedia explains Euler's identity as the equality\neiπ + 1 = 0 (equivalently eiπ = −1), where e is Euler’s number, i is the imaginary unit (i2 = −1), and π is the circle constant. It’s presented as a special case of Euler’s formula, eix = cos x + i sin x, evaluated at x = π.\n\nThe article emphasizes why the identity is famous: it links five fundamental constants (0, 1, e, i, π) and uses the three basic operations (addition, multiplication, exponentiation), so many readers regard it as a paradigmatic example of mathematical beauty. Wikipedia also outlines common derivations (for example by comparing Taylor series for eix, cos x, and sin x) and gives historical notes connecting Euler and earlier work by Roger Cotes.\n\nWould you like to see a short derivation (Taylor-series or geometric/complex-exponential) as Wikipedia presents it?","logprobs":[]}

